\subsection{Syntax}
The syntactical categories |b|, |q|, |c|, |e|, and |v| are all expressions.
The reason to distinguish them is to limit what expressions can occur where.
\begin{itemize}
\item |b|, a block with some local variables, |xs|, followed by a block body, |q|.
  The local variables can be regarded as a set; the quantification order is irrelevant.
  The variables should be distinct.
\item |q|, a sequence of equations of
  the form |v == e|.
  The equations is a sequence because order matters when there are effects.
  The '|;|' is used both to prepend and append an equation to a sequence.
\item |c|, choices are the expressions that may occur in |oneKW| and |allKW|.
\item |e|, expressions can only occur in equations, |v == e|.
\item |v|, values (as usual).  Note that lambda expressions, |lam x b|, has a block body.
\end{itemize}
It is quite easy to take an arbitrary expression and transform it to this subset.
